^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|In these lessons, in addition to deciding what card you should play at trick 1, you should be thinking about planning your defense. You should try and see how you can defeat the contract. On some of the hands, you will be asked at several different points what you should do.|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|

I certainly hope you are ready to count. Without counting, even if your instincts are good, it is impossible to defend well. What should you be trying to count? High card points. Start off by counting yours and adding it to what the dummy has. Your goal is to try and zero in on the number of points declarer has and what your partner might have. Also try to count distribution. Very often the bidding will give nice clues. When your partner makes the opening lead, thinking about which spot card he led (if he did not lead an honor) can be very helpful. Keep the Rule of 11 in mind especially in a notrump contract.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

When possible try and focus on the number of winners and losers for both your side and what the declarer might have. See where the weak spots for the declaring side might be. Of course I will offer you help. But you want to get in in the habit of giving your best effort and thinking about your defense on every hand.|
